}
```

## Process Management (systemd + Docker)
```ini
# /etc/systemd/system/kalshi-bot.service
[Unit]
Description=Kalshi Trading Bot
Requires=docker.service
After=docker.service network-online.target
StartLimitIntervalSec=300
StartLimitBurst=5            # Allow up to 5 restart attempts in 5 minutes

[Service]
Type=oneshot
RemainAfterExit=yes
WorkingDirectory=/home/botuser/kalshi-bot
ExecStart=/usr/bin/docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d
ExecStop=/usr/bin/docker compose down
ExecReload=/usr/bin/docker compose restart bot
TimeoutStartSec=120
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=10
User=botuser

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

## Auto-Recovery Scripts
```bash
#!/bin/bash
# /opt/kalshi/scripts/watchdog.sh
# Runs every minute via cron. Checks health and auto-recovers if needed.

BOT_CONTAINER="kalshi-bot"
ALERT_WEBHOOK="${ALERT_WEBHOOK_URL}"
LOG="/var/log/kalshi/watchdog.log"
LAST_RESTART_FILE="/tmp/kalshi_last_restart"

log() { echo "[$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)] $1" | tee -a "$LOG"; }
alert() { curl -s -X POST "$ALERT_WEBHOOK" -d "{\"text\": \"[WATCHDOG] $1\"}" > /dev/null; }

# Check 1: Container running?
if ! docker ps --format "{{.Names}}" | grep -q "^${BOT_CONTAINER}$"; then
    log "ALERT: Container not running. Attempting restart."
    alert "Bot container down — auto-restarting"
    docker compose -f /home/botuser/kalshi-bot/docker-compose.yml \
                   -f /home/botuser/kalshi-bot/docker-compose.prod.yml up -d
    sleep 15
fi

# Check 2: Health endpoint responding?
HEALTH=$(docker inspect --format='{{.State.Health.Status}}' "$BOT_CONTAINER" 2>/dev/null)
if [ "$HEALTH" = "unhealthy" ]; then
    log "ALERT: Container unhealthy. Restarting."
    alert "Bot health check failing — restarting container"
    docker restart "$BOT_CONTAINER"
    sleep 20
fi

# Check 3: Heartbeat fresh? (Bot writes heartbeat to DB every 60s)
HEARTBEAT_AGE=$(psql "$DATABASE_URL" -t -c "
    SELECT EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM (NOW() - (value->>'timestamp')::timestamptz))
    FROM bot_state WHERE key = 'last_heartbeat'
" 2>/dev/null | tr -d ' ')

if [ -n "$HEARTBEAT_AGE" ] && (( $(echo "$HEARTBEAT_AGE > 300" | bc -l) )); then
    log "ALERT: Heartbeat stale (${HEARTBEAT_AGE}s). Restarting bot."
    alert "Bot heartbeat stale (${HEARTBEAT_AGE}s) — restarting"
    docker restart "$BOT_CONTAINER"
fi

log "Watchdog check complete. Status: OK"
```

## Cron Jobs
```bash
# crontab -u botuser -e

# Watchdog — every minute
* * * * * /opt/kalshi/scripts/watchdog.sh

# Daily risk reset — midnight UTC
0 0 * * * /opt/kalshi/scripts/reset_daily_limits.sh

# Weekly risk reset — Monday midnight UTC
0 0 * * 1 /opt/kalshi/scripts/reset_weekly_limits.sh

# Daily backup to DO Spaces — 1 AM UTC
0 1 * * * /opt/kalshi/scripts/backup_to_spaces.sh

# Log rotation — daily
0 2 * * * /usr/sbin/logrotate /etc/logrotate.d/kalshi

# Weekly ML retraining — Sunday 11 PM UTC
0 23 * * 0 docker compose --profile training run --rm trainer

# Latency report — hourly
0 * * * * /opt/kalshi/scripts/latency_report.sh

# SSL cert check — weekly (alert if expiring in < 30 days)
0 9 * * 1 /opt/kalshi/scripts/check_ssl.sh
```

## Alerting Tiers
```
CRITICAL (page immediately, any time):
  - Bot container down and not recovering
  - Circuit breaker triggered (daily/weekly/max drawdown)
  - Kalshi API auth failure
  - Open position cannot be closed (order rejection loop)
  - Disk > 90% full

WARNING (alert, business hours OK):
  - Heartbeat stale > 3 minutes
  - Data pipeline lag > 2 minutes
  - Latency P99 > 500ms
  - Memory > 80%
  - CPU > 80% sustained > 5 minutes

INFO (daily digest):
  - Daily PnL summary
  - Trade count and win rate
  - Watchdog check results
  - Backup completion status
```

## Deployment Runbook
```bash
# Standard deploy procedure

# Step 1: Pull and review changes
git log --oneline -10   # Review what's changing

# Step 2: Run tests
docker compose run --rm bot pytest tests/ -v

# Step 3: Deploy to paper environment first
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.paper.yml up -d --build
# Monitor for 30 minutes minimum

# Step 4: Deploy to production
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.prod.yml pull
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d

# Step 5: Verify recovery
sleep 30
docker ps
docker inspect --format='{{.State.Health.Status}}' kalshi-bot
tail -f /var/log/kalshi/bot.log

# Step 6: Rollback if needed
git checkout HEAD~1
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d --build
```

## Disaster Recovery
```
Scenario 1: Droplet unresponsive
  → DO console: hard reboot
  → systemd auto-starts bot
  → Watchdog resumes within 2 minutes
  → Estimated downtime: 3–5 minutes

Scenario 2: Database corruption
  → Restore from DO Managed DB point-in-time recovery
  → Bot starts in PAUSED mode until DB validated
  → Estimated downtime: 30–60 minutes

Scenario 3: Kalshi API key compromised
  → Emergency halt via DO console (kill container)
  → Rotate key per DevOps/Security playbook
  → Redeploy with new credentials
  → Estimated downtime: 15–30 minutes
```

## Guardrails
- Never deploy directly to production without testing on paper environment first
- Never disable the watchdog cron job, even temporarily
- Keep at least 2 weeks of bot logs — they are the audit trail
- Test disaster recovery procedures quarterly — don't discover gaps during an outage
- All production changes require a rollback plan documented before deploy starts
